{"title_page": "Espresso Bongo", "text_new": "{{confused|Expresso Bongo}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2014}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=March 2014}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Espresso Bongo\n| type       = Album\n| artist     = [[Mental As Anything]]\n| cover      = Mental As Anything Espresso Bongo.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = July 1980\n| recorded   = Music Farm, Byron Bay, Australia\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Pop music|Pop]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Regular Records|Regular]]\n| producer   = [[Cameron Allan]]\n| prev_title = [[Get Wet (Mental As Anything album)|Get Wet]]\n| prev_year  = 1979\n| next_title = [[Cats & Dogs (Mental As Anything album)|Cats & Dogs]]\n| next_year  = 1981\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Espresso Bongo\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Come Around (Mental As Anything song)|Come Around]]\n | single1date = June 1980\n}}\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1     = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{rating|2|5}}<ref>{{Allmusic|class=album|id=mw0000463191}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Espresso Bongo''''' is the second studio album released by [[Mental As Anything]]. It was released in July 1980, produced by [[Cameron Allan]],<ref name=\"ARDb\">{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921103120/http://hem.passagen.se/honga/database/m/mentalasanything.html|url=http://hem.passagen.se/honga/database/m/mentalasanything.html|work=|title=Mental As Anything|publisher=[[Australian Rock Database]]. Passagen.se (Magnus Holmgren)|archivedate=21 September 2013|accessdate=1 March 2014}}</ref> and peaked at #37 on the Australian Album charts.<ref name=\"Kent\">{{cite book|title=[[Kent Music Report|Australian Chart Book 1970&ndash;1992]]|last=Kent|first=David|authorlink=David Kent (historian)|publisher=Australian Chart Book|location=[[St Ives, New South Wales|St Ives, NSW]]|year=1993|isbn=0-646-11917-6}} NOTE: Used for Australian Singles and Albums charting from 1970 until [[Australian Recording Industry Association|ARIA]] created their own [[ARIA Charts|charts]] in mid-1988.</ref> The only single released from the album, \"Come Around\", written by [[Martin Plaza]] <ref name=\"APRA Close\">{{cite web|publisher=Australasian Performing Right Association (APRA) |title=\"Close Again\" at APRA search engine |url=http://www.apra-amcos.com.au/worksearch.axd?q=Close%20Again |accessdate=19 July 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320031114/http://www.apra-amcos.com.au/worksearch.axd?q=Close%20Again |archivedate=20 March 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> was released in June 1980 and peaked at #18 on the Australian Singles charts.<ref name=\"Kent\"/> [[Virgin Records]] passed on their option to release this album overseas due to theirs and the band's dissatisfaction with the finished product.\n\nGreedy Smith later said the recording, \"just got away from us all together. We'd only learned the songs the week before we recorded them, and then we put hem down in seven days.\"<ref name=rip2>{{cite magazine| work= [[Rip It Up (magazine)|Rip It Up]] | title=Mentals: Greedy spills the beans|author=Duncan Campbell|issue=57|date=1 April 1982| url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/periodicals/RIU19820401.2.8?end_date=31-12-1985&items_per_page=10&page=13&snippet=true&start_date=01-01-1977&title=RIU}}</ref>\n\n== Track listing ==\n\n# \"Troop Movements in the Ukraine\"\n# \"Semi Trailer\"\n# \"Missing Plane\"\n# \"Insect Liberation\"\n# \"Won't Let Me Drive\"\n# \"Come Around\"\n# \"Harmonic Visions\"\n# \"Away\"\n# \"Cannibal\"\n# \"Blacktown to Bondi\"\n# \"The Girl\"\n# \"Live Now Pay Later\"\n\n==Release history==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! Region\n! Date\n! Label\n! Format\n! Catalogue\n|-\n| [[Australia]]\n| July 1980\n| Regular Records\n| Vinyl LP \n| L37358\n|-\n| [[Australia]]\n| 1992\n| Regular Records\n| CD\n| D19561\n|}\n\n==Chart positions==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Chart\n! Peak Position<ref name=\"Kent\"/>\n|-\n| 1980\n| ARIA Album Chart\n|align=\"center\"| 37\n|}\n\n==Personnel==\n===Musicians===\n* [[Martin Plaza]] &mdash; lead vocals, guitar    \n* [[Greedy Smith]] &mdash; lead vocals, keyboards, harmonica\n* [[Reg Mombassa]] &mdash; guitar, vocals  \n* [[Peter O'Doherty]] &mdash; bass, guitar, vocals \n* [[David Twohill|Wayne de Lisle]] \u2013 drums\n\n===Recording details===\n* [[Cameron Allan]] &mdash; Producer\n* Jim Blackfoot &mdash; Engineer\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Mental As Anything}}\n\n[[Category:1980 albums]]\n[[Category:Mental As Anything albums]]\n[[Category:Regular Records albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{confused|Expresso Bongo}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2014}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=March 2014}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Espresso Bongo\n| type       = Album\n| artist     = [[Mental As Anything]]\n| cover      = Mental As Anything Espresso Bongo.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = July 1980\n| recorded   = Music Farm, Byron Bay, Australia\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Pop music|Pop]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Regular Records|Regular]]\n| producer   = [[Cameron Allan]]\n| prev_title = [[Get Wet (Mental As Anything album)|Get Wet]]\n| prev_year  = 1979\n| next_title = [[Cats & Dogs (Mental As Anything album)|Cats & Dogs]]\n| next_year  = 1981\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Espresso Bongo\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Come Around (Mental As Anything song)|Come Around]]\n | single1date = June 1980\n}}\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1     = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{rating|2|5}}<ref>{{Allmusic|class=album|id=mw0000463191}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Espresso Bongo''''' is the second studio album released by [[Mental As Anything]]. It was released in July 1980, produced by [[Cameron Allan]],<ref name=\"ARDb\">{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921103120/http://hem.passagen.se/honga/database/m/mentalasanything.html|url=http://hem.passagen.se/honga/database/m/mentalasanything.html|