 South Carolina]]\n| score = 20\u201324\n}}\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{2001 WKU Hilltoppers football navbox}}\n{{Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football navbox}}\n{{2001 Division I-AA football playoff navbox}}\n{{Missouri Valley Football Conference champions}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2001 Western Kentucky Hilltoppers Football Team}}\n[[Category:2001 Gateway Football Conference season|Western Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football seasons]]\n[[Category:Missouri Valley Football Conference champion seasons]]\n[[Category:2001 in sports in Kentucky|Western Kentucky Football]]\n\n{{collegefootball-2000s-season-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season\n| mode = football\n| year = 2001\n| team= Western Kentucky Hilltoppers\n| image = WKU Hilltoppers wordmark.png\n| image_size= 175\n| conference= Gateway Football Conference\n| division= \n| short_conf= Gateway\n| STATSRank = \n| FCSCoachRank = 12\n| record = 8\u20134\n| conf_record = 5\u20132\n| head_coach= [[Jack Harbaugh]]\n| hc_year =13th\n| off_coach= \n| oc_year = \n| def_coach= \n| dc_year = \n| off_scheme= \n| def_scheme=\n| stadium= [[Houchens Industries\u2013L. T. Smith Stadium]]\n| champion = \n| bowl = NCAA Division 1-AA Playoffs\n| bowl_result = Lost First Round\n}}\n{{2001 Gateway Football Conference standings}}\nThe '''2001 Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football team''' represented [[Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football|Western Kentucky University]] in the [[2001 NCAA Division I-AA football season]] and were coached by [[Jack Harbaugh]].  This was the school\u2019s first season as a member of the [[Missouri Valley Football Conference|Gateway Football Conference]], having won the [[Ohio Valley Conference]] championship the previous year.  The Hilltoppers were the preseason favorites to win the conference but finished tied for 2nd.<ref>[https://www.bgdailynews.com/wku-tops-gateway/article_cf55498a-8294-5c01-8c1c-cafda4469002.html WKU tops Gateway, By the Daily News Online, Jul 26, 2001, retrieved 5 April 2020.]</ref>  They qualified for the NCAA Division 1-AA Playoffs where they were defeated by eventual runner-up, Furman.  The team was originally scheduled to play Wisconsin on September 14th, however, due to the [[September 11 attacks]], all college football games were suspended the following weekend, and the game was played on the 29th.<ref>[https://www.bgdailynews.com/western-hoping-to-make-up-game/article_0213a26e-61f6-5df3-b0cc-1b68a97f37da.html Western hoping to make up game, By Deborah Highland and Mitchell Plumlee, The Daily News, Sept 14, 2001, retrieved 5 April 2020.]</ref>\n<br><br>\nThis team included future [[National Football League|NFL]] players [[Joseph Jefferson (American football)|Joseph Jefferson]], [[Mel Mitchell]], [[Sherrod Coates]], and [[Brian Claybourn]].  Mitchell, Eric Dandy, and Chris Price were named to the AP All American team and Jefferson was selected to play in the Blue-Gray Football Classic.  The All-Conference team included Coates, Dandy, Jefferson, Mitchell, Price, Patrick Reynolds, Buster Ashley, Claybourn, Peter Martinez, Kyle Moffatt, and Daniel Withrow.<ref>[https://wkusports.com/documents/2019/7/17/2019_WKU_Football_Media_Guide.pdf WKU Football Media Guide retrieved 31 March 2020.]</ref>\n\n==Schedule==\n{{CFB schedule\n| rankyear = 2001\n\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = August 30\n| w/l = l\n| away = y\n| rank = 3\n| opponent = [[Western Illinois Leathernecks football|Western Illinois]]\n| opprank = 13\n| site_stadium = [[Hanson Field]]\n| site_cityst = [[Macomb, Illinois]]\n| score = 13\u201317\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 8\n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| rank = 10\n| opponent = [[Kentucky State Thorobreds football|Kentucky State]]\n| site_stadium = [[L. T. Smith Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Bowling Green, Kentucky]]\n| score = 48\u20130\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 22\n| w/l = w\n| rank = 8\n| opponent = [